      <h1>Water-Based Lubricants Guide</h1>
      <p>Pros, cons, best uses, and what you need to know about the most versatile lube type.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content">
      <p>When it comes to personal lubricants, water-based options are widely considered the gold standard for everyday use. They are versatile, easy to find, and safe for almost any sexual activity. In this guide, we'll break down the pros, cons, and best uses for water-based lubes, and discuss what ingredients you might want to look out for.</p>

      <p><em>This article is part of our comprehensive <a href="/lubricant-guide">Ultimate Guide to Personal Lubricants</a>.</em></p>

      <h2>The Pros of Water-Based Lubricant</h2>
      <p>Water-based lubes are the most popular for several excellent reasons:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Universal Condom Compatibility:</strong> They are entirely safe to use with all condoms, whether made from latex, polyurethane, or polyisoprene.</li>
        <li><strong>Toy Safe:</strong> They won't degrade silicone, rubber, glass, or plastic sex toys.</li>
        <li><strong>Easy Cleanup:</strong> Because they are water-soluble, they wash off easily with just water and rarely stain fabrics or sheets.</li>
        <li><strong>Gentle on Skin:</strong> Formulations without heavy additives tend to be gentle on sensitive mucous membranes.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The Cons and Limitations</h2>
      <p>While versatile, water-based lubes do have a few drawbacks depending on your needs:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>They Dry Out:</strong> Because they are mostly water, they absorb into the skin and evaporate. This means they can become sticky or tacky over time and require reapplication. (Pro tip: A few drops of plain water can often reactivate them).</li>
        <li><strong>Not for Water Play:</strong> Because they wash away easily, they are completely ineffective in the shower, bath, or pool.</li>
        <li><strong>Ingredient Concerns:</strong> Many common drugstore brands contain additives like glycerin or parabens that some people prefer to avoid.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Glycerin vs. Glycerin-Free</h2>
      <p>If you've ever experienced irritation or a yeast infection after using a new lube, glycerin might be the culprit. Glycerin is a sugar alcohol added to make lube feel slippery and taste sweet. However, in the delicate environment of the vagina, sugars can feed naturally occurring yeast (Candida), leading to an overgrowth and subsequent infection.</p>
      <p>For individuals prone to yeast infections, a glycerin-free water-based lubricant is highly recommended. Many high-quality, body-safe brands now proudly advertise as glycerin-free. For more on ingredient safety, see our <a href="/lube-ingredients-safety">Lube Ingredient Safety Guide</a>.</p>

      <h2>When to Choose Water-Based Lube</h2>
      <p>Water-based lubricant should be your go-to choice if:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>You are using <a href="/lube-and-condoms">latex condoms</a>.</li>
        <li>You are using silicone sex toys.</li>
        <li>You prefer easy cleanup.</li>
        <li>You are engaging in everyday penetrative or non-penetrative sex outside of the water.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If you need something longer-lasting or for water play, you might want to consider a <a href="/silicone-lube-guide">silicone-based lubricant</a> instead.</p>

      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <h3>Is water-based lube safe with condoms?</h3>
        <p>Yes, water-based lubricant is completely safe to use with all types of condoms, including latex, polyurethane, and polyisoprene.</p>

        <h3>Why does water-based lube get sticky?</h3>
        <p>Water-based lubes can become sticky as the water evaporates or is absorbed by the skin. You can easily reactivate the slickness by adding a few drops of water or saliva.</p>

        <h3>Are glycerin-free lubes better?</h3>
        <p>For many people, yes. Glycerin is a sugar alcohol that can sometimes trigger yeast infections in those prone to them. Glycerin-free options are often recommended for better vaginal health.</p>
      </div>

      <p>Return to the <a href="/lubricant-guide">Main Lubricant Guide</a> for more information on different lube types.</p>
    </div>
